46 11 CHAP. 52. See chapter on military affaim, vu, for description of a battle—singulos legatos, etc.: i.e. a leg-atus in command qs each legion. This was the beginning of a very important reform in the military organization. Caesar felt so keenly the evil of the command being divided among six tribunes that he detailed one of his legati nominally to assist the tribuneS. After this time we find the legatus as the regular com- mander of a legion, with the six tribunes under him. On this occasion, having only five legati, he also appointed his quartermaster (quaestor) to that one of the six legions which was intended to be under his own special command.
